According to the conjunction fallacy, the probability of two events occurring together (in "and" statements) is always less than or equal to the probability of either one occurring alone. Therefore, the probability of the woman having both a skin rash and a thyroid nodule is less likely than her having only a skin rash, which is a classic symptom of chickenpox.
